Subject:    <a href="?t=95837890400004&r=1&w=2">Resolving partially qualified domain names</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837785600005&r=1&w=2">pc () bellcore ! com</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198807">1988-07-26 18:25:12</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783026915&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783026915&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

It would be convenient to be able to resolve certain domain names
without going all the way back to the root servers....if my
fully-qualified domain name is "alex.ctt.bellcore.com" (which it is...)
and i wish to resolve "tower.cc.bellcore.com" current protocol says i
must get a root domain server to find an IP address for the
"bellcore.com" domain, and so forth, which is clearly wasteful.

I heard rumours of discussion about resolving a name such as
"tower.cc.bellcore" which would establish a "root" at the "bellcore"
end, from which i can ask for an IP address for the "cc.bellcore"
domain.  Can someone fill me in as to the results of those proposals? 

Also, it would be nice to be able to give a "user-friendly" domain name,
such as being able to distinguish between:

	alex.bellcore.com
and     alex.ctt.bellcore.com

from some machine (say flash.bellcore.com) by using the names:

	alex
and	alex.ctt

that is, assuming a prefix domain name of "bellcore.com".  This i
suppose, begs the question of how to refer to the two from a host:
dduck.ctt.bellcore.com, without doing

	alex
and	alex.bellcore.com


Oh well.

Peter Clitherow, Bellcore,
  444 Hoes Lane, Room 1H-213,
  Piscataway, NJ 08854

